            <h3><center>WHAT IS METASTASIS?</center></h3>
<p>Metastasis refers to when cancer in one part of the body migrates from the origin to other locations in the body. 
Nearly all cancers can <i>metastasize,</i> however, this is dependent on <br>several - factors such as the size, type and origin of the primary tumor.</p> 


<div class="content">
<img src="images/metastasis.jpg" alt="Metastasis of Cancer"> 
<div>
<p>Metastasis can occur in three different ways.<br> 
<b>The cancer cells can:</b>
<ul>
  <li>Grow into the surrounding tissues surrounding the primary tumor.
  <li>Travel through the bloodstream to distant locations.
  <li>Migrate through the lymphatic system to nearby or distant lymphatic nodes.
</ul>
<hr>
<p>Metastasis may also be referred to or known as <b><i>metastatic cancer, stage IV (4) cancer, secondary cancer, or cancer with mets.</i></b></p>

</div>
</div>


<h3>Which Cancers Metastasize?</h3>
Almost all cancers can migrate around the human body. Some of these include:
<ul>  
  <li>Breast cancer</li>
  <li>Colorectal cancer</li>
  <li>Esophageal cancer</li>
  <li>Lung cancer</li>
  <li>Ovarian cancer</li>
  <li>Pancreatic cancer</li>
  <li>Prostate cancer</li>
  <li>Skin cancers</li>
  <li>Stomach cancer</li>
  <li>Uterine cancer</li>
</ul>

<h3>Where Does Cancer Metastasize First?</h3>
Where cancer metastasis first depends on the origin of the primary tumor. Some of the most common locations of metastasis in the body are the 
<ul>
  <li>Adrenal glands</li> 
  <li>Bones</li> 
  <li>Brain</li> 
  <li>Liver</li> 
  <li>Lungs </li>
  <li>Lymph nodes</li> 
  <li>Peritoneum</li>
</ul>


